South Washington County Schools (SoWashCo) is happy to share that Kelly Jansen started as the Assistant Superintendent of Academic Excellence and Accountability on Sept. 2. Ms. Jansen is a familiar face in the district, having served as our Director of Teaching and Learning Services since 2018.

Ms. Jansen will assist with the hiring of her replacement for director of teaching and learning and will work closely with Assistant Superintendents Kristine Shaefer and Dr. Tyrone Brookins to ensure a smooth transition. Ms. Jansen oversees SoWashCo’s four middle schools with additional oversight for several departments to be announced at a later date.

Read more: https://www.sowashco.org/cms/One.aspx?portalId=1217437&pageId=27847960

South Washington County Schools has started a new family technology support phone line at 651-425-HELP (4357).

Standard phone line hours are Monday through Friday from 7:30 a.m. to 4 p.m. You can leave a voicemail at any time with your child’s name, the school they attend and a call back number, and someone will return your call.

*Due to the high volume of calls, it may take longer for SoWashCo technology specialists to get back to you.
Student passwords can either be found in your parent portal account or by calling your child's school.

post_text:
From a stockpile of sanitizers and personal protective equipment to new electrical misters, join incoming Superintendent Julie Nielsen for a tour of some of the changes that students, staff and families will see for the new school year.

Our facilities staff, principals, educators and so many more have been working throughout the summer to plan for the return of students.

Until we have a safe and effective vaccine, we don’t know what the rate of infection will be like in our communities. Our work as a district is to do everything we can to prevent the transmission of the virus. This includes wearing face coverings, hand washing and social distancing. No one thing will stop the spread COVID-19, but we have protocols and procedures in place to create those layers of prevention.

Please join us in welcoming Wayne Felton II as our new Director of Achievement and Integration. Mr. Felton brings a wealth of experience in helping students and staff succeed.

Most recently, he served as an associate administrator for Heritage Middle School in West St. Paul. Previously, Mr. Felton worked as a coordinator of education equity at Independent School District 622 in North St. Paul and an equity coach and behavior specialist at Independent School District 623 in Roseville where he oversaw all achievement and integration programming, served as a member of the teaching and learning team to help create curriculum, surveys and programs, and developed equity professional development for both licensed and non-licensed staff.

Read more: https://www.sowashco.org/cms/One.aspx?portalId=1217437&pageId=27775804

Assistant Superintendent Julie Nielsen has been named as the next superintendent for South Washington County Schools beginning Sept. 2. She will succeed Dr. Keith Jacobus following his July announcement to retire.

During a school board meeting on Aug. 13, seven members of the board unanimously appointed Mrs. Nielsen to the top leadership position. She is the first female superintendent for South Washington County Schools.

Please give her a warm welcome as she steps into her new role.

During a special school board meeting on Monday, Aug. 3, SoWashCo presented its safe learning plan for the new school year. Following a review of distance learning and in-person learning, the school board voted to move forward on planning for hybrid learning in the event it’s needed this fall.

The school board also directed the superintendent to be more restrictive by one level than the Minnesota Department of Education (MDE) Safe Learning Plan. Under this direction and if school was to be held today, all students would start in hybrid learning.

The school board will make the final decision on how school will start this fall during its board meeting on Aug. 13.

Read more: https://sowashco.org/cms/One.aspx?portalId=1217437&pageId=27476095

post_text:
We understand the incredible anxiety for families and staff as they prepare for the new school year.

Today, the state set thresholds for schools to reopen safely based on a formula that uses COVID-19 infection rates. If SoWashCo schools were to be held today, elementary school students (K-5) could attend school in-person, and secondary school students (6-12) could be in a hybrid model.

Our planning and leadership teams will spend the weekend reviewing and comparing the state’s recommendations to our draft plans and will make revisions as needed. We anticipate sharing a recommendation to our school board during a special board meeting on Monday, Aug. 3 at 6:30 p.m.

Please know that we are working as quickly as possible to provide a detailed and thorough plan for the start of the school year.

Read more: https://www.sowashco.org/cms/One.aspx?portalId=1217437&pageId=27430925

South Washington County Schools is conducting virtual focus groups to present and gather feedback on a hybrid model as a possible scenario for the upcoming school year. The hybrid model is a combination of in-person learning at school and distance learning at home.

Several sessions will be offered each day, from Tuesday, July 28 to Thursday, July 30 and will last approximately one hour.

***Focus groups scheduled for Thursday, July 30 have been canceled. If you missed the live presentation, a recorded session is available below. Feedback can be provided by survey until 11:59 p.m., Friday, July 31.***

To learn more and sign up visit: https://sowashco.org/cms/One.aspx?portalId=1217437&pageId=27334209

Watch a recorded session: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gpLWeofsEZM

Focus group survey: https://sowashco.co1.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_e2nNA9yfJENfK3H

After the Governor’s announcement, we’ll fine-tune and release additional details for the start of the 2020-21 school year by August 14.

As a regional and national speaker and trainer for Advancement Via Individual Determination (AVID), Dr. Brookins brings a great deal of knowledge and strategies for incorporating the success of AVID into a school system.

We're continuing our Class of 2020 Senior Spotlight Series with Sophie Wu from Woodbury High School, who will be attending Stanford University in the fall.

"I’ve learned that I genuinely enjoy the act of learning itself. I won’t lie and say that I’m always excited to walk into class or complete an assignment, but over the years, I’ve been able to take away something from every subject I’ve been exposed to. The idea that, as long as we put the time into it, we can learn anything, is pretty cool.”

Read more about Sophie at: https://www.sowashco.org/cms/One.aspx?portalId=1217437&pageId=26893777

We're continuing our Class of 2020 Senior Spotlight Series with Miles Lee from East Ridge High School.

"With the current status of the world, what gives me hope is the future with my friends and family. I hope that in the future my friends and I can go back out to the river and catch fish, or that my newborn twin nieces grow up to be smart and happy kids. In a time of constant change and irregularities, it is things like that keep me moving every day."

To help celebrate the Class of 2020, we asked high school principals to identify exemplary seniors to be profiled for our Class of 2020 Senior Spotlight series.

First, hear from Hermione Joseph a senior at East Ridge High School: "The most important thing I have learned in school is to put yourself out there. Whether it be a club or a sport, there is nothing more satisfactory than completing something you didn’t know you could do! For me, this was starting Cross Country as a junior with no running experience and then being elected as a captain for the team my senior year! I also participated in Track, Youth Advisory Council, Student Council, UNIFIED Club and Fellowship of Christian Athletes."

Read more about Hermoine at: https://www.sowashco.org/news/latest_news/2020_senior_spotlight__hermione_joseph_

post_text:
3M recently donated $270,000 to South Washington County Schools to support our distance learning and emergency response to COVID-19.

"We are grateful for the generous financial contribution from 3M to help meet our unexpected distance learning needs," said Superintendent Keith Jacobus. "These funds strengthen our goal to ensure each child receives the support they need while learning at home."

The contribution will enhance distance learning enrichment, fund hotspot devices for families who require internet service and provide social and emotional support. Meals will also be provided through weekend food packs through the SoWashCo CARES foundation for families in need.

Thank you for your support.

post_text:
Schoology Update: Yesterday, Schoology, as well as Google, experienced an overload relating to the Google Drive Assignment app. Over the next few days, Google and Schoology are going to disable the Google Drive Assignment app between the hours of 10:30 a.m. to 1:30 p.m. Central Time until the engineering teams are able to complete their work. There will be a banner on the Schoology site when the app is disabled.

Teachers have been provided a “workaround” for this issue and many of them will be using it with your students beginning today, Friday, April 3. Teachers will provide additional instructions if students need to turn in their work through Schoology with this “workaround”.

Schoology says they are working to stabilize their service. We appreciate your patience and your teachers will continue to be flexible as we learn together.

South Washington County Schools is opening Emergency Child Care at no cost to families who qualify. Emergency Child Care is open to currently enrolled students in kindergarten-grade 5 for parents or guardians who are defined as an emergency responder that is crucial to the prevention and treatment of COVID-19.

If you do not qualify for Emergency Child Care but are interested in receiving free meals for your child, registration is available. Meals will be offered at no cost for anyone under 18 years of age (upon request).

More information and registration available here: https://www.sowashco.org/cms/One.aspx?portalId=1217437&pageId=26250290

All South Washington County Schools will be closed for student classes from Monday, March 16, through Friday, March 27. Employees will continue to be paid during this closure. We understand you may have questions. We are currently creating plans and will provide additional information as it becomes available. For the latest updates, please visit sowashco.org.

The Minnesota Senate E-12 committee recognized Newport Elementary as a “Beating the Odds” school! The recognition was earned for having high academic performance in math and reading while having above-average concentrations of students of color, free and reduced-price lunch eligible students and English Language Learners.

The principal of Newport Elementary Rich Romano and Assistant Superintendent Kristine Schaefer presented program elements that contribute to student success at a Senate E-12 Committee meeting on Feb. 19.

post_text: Congratulations to Lake Middle School eighth grade student Alexis Casner, who won the 2019 Maurice R. Hilleman Essay Contest offered by the Vaccine Education Center at Children’s Hospital of Philadelphia. She won with her 600-word essay on “How would the world be different if Dr. Hilleman had not lived the life he did?” Dr. Hilleman was a microbiologist, who specialized in vaccinology, who developed more than 40 vaccines, including measles, mumps, hepatitis A, hepatitis B, meningitis, pneumonia and rubella. His vaccines have been credited with saving millions of lives and with eradicating common childhood diseases. Read more: https://www.sowashco.org/cms/One.aspx?portalId=1217437&pageId=22853133

Read more: https://www.sowashco.org/cms/One.aspx?portalId=1217437&pageId=21998012

post_text: The first day of school for the 19-20 school year is in the books! We were excited to welcome back our students in kindergarten through ninth grade this morning. We'll see students in grades 10-12 tomorrow.

post_text: We're so proud of our students! They always find ways to give back to their community. Thanks to Cub Scout Pack 56 for their work to clean up around Red Rock Elementary School! We can't wait for school to start!
shared_text:
Red Rock Elementary
August 22, 2019 at 1:58 PM ·

Thank you, Cub Scout Pack 56, for cleaning up our Red Rock campus! They picked up trash and pulled weeds to help ensure that our grounds are clean and ready for our students' return! Way to go, scouts!

post_text: Attention parents! Our District Service Center in Cottage Grove will be open late as we prepare for the new school year. Our Student Information Office will be open from 7 a.m. to 7 p.m. on Aug. 20, 22, 27, 29, and Sept. 3. Check out www.sowashco.org/back_to_school to find more important information for back-to-school, including school supply lists, a printable school year calendar and more!
